      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read this entire manual before assembly or use.</strong> Failure to follow safety instructions can result in serious personal injury, electric shock, or fire.
      </div>

      <h3>Key Safety Warnings</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Always wear safety glasses. Use a face or dust mask if the cutting operation is dusty.</li>
        <li>Use the blade guard and spreader for every operation for which it can be used, including all through-sawing.</li>
        <li>Keep hands out of the line of the saw blade. Never reach around or over the blade.</li>
        <li>Use a push stick when your hand comes within 6 inches of the blade.</li>
        <li>Know how to reduce the risk of kickback. Feed work into the blade against the direction of rotation only.</li>
        <li>Never perform any operation freehand. Always use a fence (rip cuts) or miter gauge (cross-cuts).</li>
        <li>A rip fence must be installed before using the saw for rip cutting.</li>
        <li>Keep children and visitors at a safe distance from the work area.</li>
        <li>Turn the main power switch to OFF and unplug the power cord before servicing, changing blades, or changing brake cartridges.</li>
        <li>Never leave the saw running unattended. Wait until the blade comes to a complete stop before leaving.</li>
        <li>Do not wear loose clothing, gloves, neckties, rings, bracelets, or jewelry near moving parts.</li>
        <li>Do not force the tool. Use the right blade for the job.</li>
        <li>Do not unplug or disconnect the saw from electrical power before the blade has stopped spinning.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Electrical Safety</h3>
      <p>The saw must be connected to a grounded wiring system. The plug must match a properly installed and grounded outlet per local codes. Do not modify the plug.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Extension Cord Sizing (110&ndash;120V):</strong> 0&ndash;25 ft: 12 AWG; 25&ndash;50 ft: 10 AWG; over 50 ft: not recommended. For 208&ndash;240V: 0&ndash;50 ft: 16 AWG; 50&ndash;100 ft: 14 AWG; 100&ndash;200 ft: 12 AWG. Always use 3-wire cords with grounding plugs.
      </div>

      <h2>The SawStop Safety System</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p13_00.jpg" alt="SawStop brake cartridge showing the sealed housing, brake pawl, and mounting holes" />
        <figcaption>SawStop brake cartridge</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>The SawStop safety system includes two components: an electronic detection unit and a fast-acting brake. A small electrical signal is induced onto the blade. When human skin contacts the blade, a portion of the signal is absorbed by the body's electrical capacitance, and the detection unit recognizes this as contact.</p>

      <p>The fast-acting brake includes a fuse holding a strong spring in compression. When contact is detected, the fuse is burned by a surge of electric current, and the spring pushes an aluminum pawl into the teeth of the spinning blade, stopping it in approximately 3&ndash;5 milliseconds. If the blade is at or near full speed, it also quickly retracts below the table.</p>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Non-conductive materials</strong> (wood, plastic, foam, Corian, melamine) do not trigger the brake. <strong>Conductive materials</strong> (aluminum, other metals, carbon fiber, mirrored acrylic) will typically activate the brake. Use Bypass Mode for conductive materials.
      </div>

      <h3>Important Safety System Points</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Do not rely solely on the safety system &mdash; always use safe practices, the blade guard, and push sticks.</li>
        <li>Do not operate in Bypass Mode unless cutting electrically conductive material.</li>
        <li>Use only standard 10" steel blades with kerfs from 3/32" to 3/16". Do not use non-conductive blades, molding heads, or blades with coated teeth.</li>
        <li>Never stack two or more 10" blades.</li>
        <li>Do not use table inserts, guards, or fences with metal parts that may contact the blade.</li>
        <li>Allow wet pressure-treated wood to fully dry before cutting (24 hours unstacked in a dry location).</li>
        <li>Do not replace the arbor belt with a non-SawStop belt (the SawStop belt dissipates static electricity).</li>
        <li>Never touch the arbor, arbor pulley, arbor nut, or arbor washer when the blade is spinning.</li>
      </ul>

