      <h2>Unpacking &amp; Standing Up Your Saw</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>The saw weighs approximately 317 lbs with extension wings.</strong> Use proper lifting technique and get help from another person.
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove all packing materials and accessories before removing the saw from the shipping pallet. Verify all components are included.</li>
        <li>Place the top Styrofoam piece with one short side next to the pallet by the back of the saw. Position so both the table top edge and the bottom cabinet edge overhang the Styrofoam.</li>
        <li>With help, carefully roll the saw off the pallet onto the Styrofoam. Use the cast iron table and elevation control shaft as lifting points.</li>
        <li>With help, carefully tip the saw to the upright position by lifting under the rear edge of the cast iron table. Lift slowly so it slides off the Styrofoam onto the floor.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        If you have a Professional Cabinet Saw Mobile Base, install it now while the saw is on its side before standing it up.
      </div>

      <h2>Assembly</h2>

      <p><strong>Tools required:</strong> Phillips screwdriver, 13 mm wrench, 14 mm wrench, level or straight edge, plus hex keys from the hardware pack (M3, M4, M5, M6, M8).</p>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Clean the table top:</strong> Remove the plastic covering and yellow label from the table insert. Wipe oil from the cast iron table top and extension wings with a soft cloth.</li>
        <li><strong>Install the elevation handwheel:</strong> Screw the handle into the handwheel, tighten with a 14 mm wrench. Insert a key into the slot at the end of the elevation control shaft. Slide the handwheel on flush, install the M6 set screw (3 mm hex key), and screw in the lock knob.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p30_00.jpg" alt="Elevation handwheel installation showing key insertion into control shaft slot" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p30_01.jpg" alt="Elevation handwheel mounted on shaft with lock knob" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Install the tilt handwheel:</strong> Same procedure as the elevation handwheel, using the tilt control shaft. Use the lock knob with the shorter shaft.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p31_00.jpg" alt="Tilt handwheel parts showing key, handwheel, and set screw" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Install the dust port:</strong> Insert the dust port (with semicircle key) from inside the cabinet into the 4" hole at the back. Secure with three M5 screws and lock washers from the outside.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p32_00.jpg" alt="Dust port with semicircle key on the flange for proper orientation" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p32_01.jpg" alt="Dust port inserted into cabinet hole from inside" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p32_02.jpg" alt="Securing dust port with screws from outside the cabinet" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Install the motor cover:</strong> Hold the motor cover against the side of the saw with the two arrows pointing to the two metal tubes on the cabinet. Slip the motor cover rod through the lower tube, half-cylinders on the cover, and upper tube. Rotate the bent end into the hook on the cover.
          <div class="image-row">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p33_00.jpg" alt="Motor cover positioned against cabinet with arrows aligned to tubes" />
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p33_01.jpg" alt="Motor cover rod installation through tubes and half-cylinders" />
          </div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Mount the extension wings:</strong> Position each cast iron extension wing (chamfer toward front) on either side of the table. Mount with four M8 hex bolts, washers, and lock washers each (finger tight). Use a straight edge to level the wings with the table top, then tighten all bolts with a 13 mm wrench.
          <div class="figure">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p34_00.jpg" alt="Extension wing aligned and bolted to the cast iron table" />
            <figcaption>Extension wings mounted to table</figcaption>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Mount the switch box:</strong> Mount under the left extension wing using two M6 x 20 button head socket screws with lock washers and washers (4 mm hex key).
          <div class="figure">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p35_00.jpg" alt="Switch box mounted under left extension wing showing status code label" />
            <figcaption>Switch box with system status codes label</figcaption>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Mount the accessory holders:</strong> Mount the blade wrench holder to the left side of the cabinet behind the switch box. Mount the accessory tool holder (for riving knife, miter gauge, blade guard) to the front lower right side of the cabinet. Each uses one M6 x 12 screw with lock washer.
          <div class="figure">
            <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p36_00.jpg" alt="Blade wrench holder and accessory tool holder mounted on the cabinet" />
            <figcaption>Accessory holders installed</figcaption>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        You must install a rip fence prior to using the saw. Refer to the manual accompanying your rip fence for installation instructions.
      </div>

      <h2>Preparing Your Saw for Use</h2>

      <h3>Table Insert Removal &amp; Installation</h3>
      <p>The table insert is held by two rear lock-down screws and a rotating lock-down lever at the front. To remove, rotate the lock-down lever upward and lift the front, angling the insert to clear the spreader or riving knife. To install, reverse the process. Ensure no part of the insert extends above the table surface.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        Never operate the saw without the table insert in place. Do not use inserts with metal parts that could contact the blade.
      </div>

      <h3>Blade or Dado Installation</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p37_00.jpg" alt="Using blade wrenches to loosen the arbor nut for blade installation" />
        <figcaption>Using blade wrenches for blade installation</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Turn off main power and unplug the power cord.</li>
        <li>Remove the table insert.</li>
        <li>Use the open end of one blade wrench to hold the arbor behind the flange, and the closed end of the other to loosen the arbor nut (right-hand threaded &mdash; turn counter-clockwise to loosen).</li>
        <li>Remove the arbor nut and washer. Install the blade (teeth pointing toward the front/top) and reinstall the washer and nut. Tighten securely.</li>
        <li>For dado sets wider than about 3/8", do not use the arbor washer &mdash; tighten the nut directly against the dado set.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Brake Position Adjustment</h3>
      <p>The spacing between the brake cartridge and blade must be between 1/16" and 1/8". Adjust using the yellow brake positioning bolt (8 mm hex key) in the top of the arbor block. Clockwise decreases spacing; counter-clockwise increases it. You can use the included blade spacing adjustment gauge or a U.S. nickel to set the gap.</p>

      <div class="danger">
        After adjusting, always spin the blade by hand at least one full revolution to verify the blade does not contact the brake.
      </div>

      <h3>Blade Guard &amp; Riving Knife</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p40_00.jpg" alt="Releasing the quick-release clamp to remove the riving knife" />
      </div>
      <p>The quick-release clamp allows tool-free removal and installation. Lift the clamping handle fully upward, move the riving knife or spreader slightly right to clear the pins, and lift out. To install, position the component in the clamp against the base plate and lower the handle to lock.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Blade guard:</strong> Use for all through-sawing. The side guards float on the workpiece (up to 3-1/8" high). The polycarbonate construction provides clear visibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Riving knife:</strong> Use whenever the blade guard cannot be used (rabbet cuts, non-through cuts, narrow cuts where guard interferes with fence).</li>
        <li>Neither can be used with dado sets.</li>
        <li>Both are 2.3 mm (0.090") thick &mdash; do not use blades with kerf less than 2.35 mm.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Dust Collection</h3>
      <p>Connect a 4" diameter hose from your dust collector to the dust port at the back of the cabinet. SawStop recommends at least 350 CFM of flow at the dust port. The internal dust shroud provides superior dust collection.</p>

      <h3>Electrical Power Connection</h3>
      <p>The PCS175 motor is rated at 1.75 HP and comes pre-wired for 115V (compatible with 110&ndash;120V power). It draws 14 amps at 120V. Connect to a 20 amp breaker circuit.</p>

      <div class="note">
        The saw can be re-wired for 208&ndash;240V power, which requires purchasing a 230V contactor box assembly (PCS-WA-025) and rewiring the motor junction box. See the full PDF manual for the detailed wiring procedure.
      </div>

      <h3>Re-Wiring for 208&ndash;240V</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p44_00.jpg" alt="Motor junction box location underneath the motor" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p44_01.jpg" alt="NEMA 6-15P plug for 208-240V power connection" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Replace the contactor assembly with the 230V version (PCS-WA-025).</li>
        <li>Open the motor cover and locate the junction box underneath the motor.</li>
        <li>Remove the junction box cover. Disconnect the existing wire nut connections.</li>
        <li>Rewire per the 208&ndash;240V wiring diagram: connect black power cord wire to white motor wire; white power cord wire to red motor wire; black motor wire to yellow motor wire.</li>
        <li>Wrap each wire nut with two layers of electrical tape.</li>
        <li>Double-check wiring against the schematic, then reattach the junction box cover.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <h3>Adjusting Blade Height</h3>
      <p>For through-cuts, set the blade 1/8" to 1/2" above the workpiece. Loosen the elevation lock knob, turn the elevation handwheel clockwise to raise / counter-clockwise to lower (range: 1/8" below table to 3-1/8" above). Lock the knob when set.</p>

      <h3>Adjusting Blade Tilt</h3>
      <p>Loosen the tilt lock knob, turn the tilt handwheel counter-clockwise to increase the angle (0&deg;&ndash;45&deg;). The tilt indicator shows the current angle. Lock the knob when set.</p>

      <div class="note">
        When reaching the limit stops, reverse the handwheel slightly to release tension. This prevents twisting of the cast iron assembly that could affect blade alignment.
      </div>

      <h3>Starting the Motor</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p45_00.jpg" alt="Switch box showing main power switch, Start/Stop paddle, and lockout key" />
        <figcaption>Switch box controls</figcaption>
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Ensure the Start/Stop paddle is pushed in (OFF).</li>
        <li>Flip the main power switch toggle upward (ON). The safety system will run a 5&ndash;10 second initialization routine.</li>
        <li>Wait for the green LED to display solid (READY status).</li>
        <li>Pull the Start/Stop paddle out to start the motor.</li>
        <li>Push the paddle in to stop the motor (can be pushed with upper leg or knee in emergencies).</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p46_00.jpg" alt="Main power switch lockout key that can be removed to prevent unauthorized use" />
        <figcaption>Main power switch lockout key</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>The main power switch has a removable lockout key to prevent unauthorized use. A thermal overload switch on the contactor box will cut motor power if overheating occurs &mdash; wait 1&ndash;2 minutes, then press the red reset button.</p>

