      <h3>Using the Blade Guard</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p50_00.jpg" alt="Blade guard installed showing side guards, anti-kickback pawls, spreader, wood stop, and top guard" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p50_01.jpg" alt="Pulling top guard forward and up to release from spreader" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p50_02.jpg" alt="Top guard balanced upright against spreader for blade access" />
      </div>
      <p>The blade guard has a narrow profile that allows use even during narrow rip cuts. The side guards pivot to automatically adjust to the workpiece height. The top guard can be placed upright or removed without tools for blade changes.</p>
      <p>Anti-kickback pawls can be disabled by rotating them upward, or removed entirely by pulling the bolt back to stretch the spring.</p>

      <h3>Cross-Cutting</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p54_00.jpg" alt="Cross-cutting with miter gauge in the right slot, workpiece held against face" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p54_01.jpg" alt="Cross-cutting procedure showing smooth push through the blade" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Use the miter gauge in the right miter slot for bevel cuts, or either slot for non-bevel cuts.</li>
        <li>Remove or reposition the rip fence so it does not contact the workpiece during cross-cutting.</li>
        <li>Set blade elevation to about 1/8" above the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Align the cut, pull the miter gauge and workpiece back, then start the motor.</li>
        <li>Push the workpiece slowly and smoothly past the blade. Shift away from blade before pulling back.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Rip Cutting</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p55_00.jpg" alt="Rip cutting with both hands pushing workpiece flat against table and flush with fence" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p55_01.jpg" alt="Rip cutting showing proper hand position keeping at least 6 inches from blade" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Always use a rip fence for rip cuts. Never rip freehand.</li>
        <li>Set blade elevation to about 1/8" above the workpiece. Lock the fence at the desired width.</li>
        <li>Position the workpiece flat on the table and flush against the fence.</li>
        <li>Use both hands to push the workpiece smoothly toward the blade, maintaining at least 6" between hands and blade.</li>
        <li>When your hand closest to the blade comes within 6", remove it and use a push stick to finish the cut.</li>
        <li>Use a featherboard clamped to the table to hold the workpiece against the fence when using a push stick.</li>
        <li>For pieces longer than 4 feet, use an out-feed table or rollers.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Push stick usage:</strong> Always use a push stick or push block when your hand comes within 6 inches of the blade. For cuts too narrow for a push stick, use an auxiliary fence and push block.
      </div>

      <h3>Bypass Mode</h3>
      <p>Use Bypass Mode only when cutting electrically conductive materials (aluminum, metals, carbon fiber).</p>
      <ol>
        <li>With paddle OFF, turn main power ON. Wait for READY status.</li>
        <li>Turn the Bypass Key clockwise and hold for at least 1 second (red LED flashes once).</li>
        <li>While still holding the key, pull the Start/Stop paddle out. The blade will start spinning.</li>
        <li>Continue holding the key for at least 1 second after the motor starts (red LED flashes again).</li>
        <li>When finished, push the paddle in. Bypass Mode automatically ends when the blade stops.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p57_00.jpg" alt="Bypass key location on the switch box" />
        <figcaption>Bypass key on the switch box</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Changing the Brake Cartridge</h3>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p60_00.jpg" alt="Standard 10-inch brake cartridge showing cartridge key, brake pawl, and sealed housing" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p60_01.jpg" alt="8-inch dado brake cartridge with wider brake pawl for dado sets" />
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Turn off main power and unplug the power cord.</li>
        <li>Set tilt to 0&deg; and raise blade to maximum height. Remove the table insert.</li>
        <li>Rotate the blade guard clamping handle fully upward.</li>
        <li>Turn the cartridge key 90&deg; clockwise and pull it away from the cartridge.</li>
        <li>Slide the cartridge to the right off the pivot pin and positioning pin.</li>
        <li>If the brake has fired, the pawl is typically locked onto the blade &mdash; remove both together by alternately "walking" the blade and cartridge to the right off the arbor and pins.</li>
        <li>To install a new cartridge, align mounting holes with the pivot and positioning pins. Slide on, insert the cartridge key (red handle pointing toward brake pawl), and rotate 90&deg; counter-clockwise to lock.</li>
        <li>Adjust brake position and verify spacing before use.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>What to Do if the Safety System Activates</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Reset the arbor block retraction:</strong> Turn the elevation handwheel counter-clockwise until the lower limit stop is reached. The arbor block will re-engage the retraction bracket. Then turn clockwise to raise the blade.</li>
        <li><strong>Replace the brake cartridge:</strong> The activated cartridge is expended and cannot be reused. If activation was due to skin contact, return the cartridge to SawStop for a free replacement.</li>
        <li><strong>Replace the blade:</strong> The brake pawl usually locks onto the blade and pulls off carbide teeth. Replace or repair the blade.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Adjustments</h2>

      <h3>Table Alignment</h3>
      <p>The miter slots should be parallel to the blade for accurate cuts. Use a dial test indicator (0.0005" resolution) mounted in the miter slot, measuring at front and rear of the blade. The table is aligned via a front pivot pin and rear positioning screws (5 mm hex key). Loosen the four table mounting bolts (17 mm wrench) before adjusting.</p>

      <h3>Blade-to-Tilt-Axis Alignment</h3>
      <p>SawStop cabinet saws uniquely allow fine-tuning the parallelism of the blade to the tilt axis, ensuring accurate bevel cuts. This requires measuring alignment at both 0&deg; and 45&deg; tilt with a dial indicator. See the full PDF manual for the detailed procedure.</p>

      <h3>Tilt &amp; Elevation Limit Stops</h3>
      <p>The 0&deg; and 45&deg; tilt limit stops and the upper elevation limit stop are factory pre-set. They can be adjusted if needed using the appropriate hex keys. See the full PDF manual for details.</p>

      <h3>Quick-Release Clamp Adjustment</h3>
      <p>The clamping force for the riving knife and spreader can be increased or decreased. See the full PDF manual for instructions.</p>

      <h3>Miter Gauge Adjustment</h3>
      <p>The miter gauge has adjustable index stops at -45&deg;, 0&deg;, and +45&deg;. Three spring bearings in the main bar ensure smooth sliding in the T-slots. Both are factory pre-set.</p>

      <h3>Belt Tension</h3>
      <p>The motor belt should deflect no more than about 1/4" with light finger pressure. Adjust by loosening the two motor bolts (19 mm socket wrench) and lowering the motor slightly. The arbor belt cannot be tightened and must be replaced if it slips under load.</p>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always turn off the main power switch and unplug the power cord before performing any maintenance.
      </div>

      <h3>Safety System</h3>
      <p>The safety system performs continuous self-checks. No user maintenance is required beyond monitoring status codes.</p>

      <h3>Brake Cartridge</h3>
      <p>Check the cartridge condition every 50 hours of use. The cartridge is sealed against dust. Replace if a significant amount of dust is visible inside the clear plastic housing.</p>

      <h3>Elevation &amp; Tilt Mechanisms</h3>
      <p>Keep elevation shafts and gearing clean and lubricated. Periodically clean the elevation worm gear, threaded rod, tilt sector gear, and trunnion brackets with a wire brush, then apply non-hardening grease. Lubricate handwheel shaft bushings with lightweight penetrating oil.</p>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p89_00.jpg" alt="Front lubrication points showing sector gear, elevation handwheel shaft bushing, pinion gear, front and rear trunnion brackets, and tilt handwheel shaft bushing" />
        <figcaption>Front lubrication points</figcaption>
      </div>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/sawstop-pcs/p89_01.jpg" alt="Rear lubrication points showing threaded rod and worm gear" />
        <figcaption>Rear lubrication points</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Cabinet</h3>
      <p>Keep the interior free of accumulated sawdust, wood chips, and debris. Periodically vacuum out the cabinet and trunnion assembly.</p>

      <h3>Table &amp; Extension Wings</h3>
      <p>Keep surfaces clean and rust-free. Remove rust by spraying WD-40 and scrubbing with a fine abrasive pad (Scotch-Brite 7448). Prevent rust with GlideCote or TopSaver. For long-term storage, apply a light coat of oil and cover with wax paper.</p>

      <h3>Belts</h3>
      <p>Check the arbor belt and motor belt periodically for wear or damage. Replace any worn or damaged belts. The arbor belt is static-dissipative &mdash; always replace with a SawStop belt.</p>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>

      <h3>Motor Will Not Start (Both LEDs Off)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Verify electrical supply is on and correct voltage is being supplied.</li>
        <li>Verify a brake cartridge is installed.</li>
        <li>Try a different brake cartridge (defective cartridge).</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Motor Will Not Start (At Least One LED On)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Consult the System Status Codes to determine the error and corrective action.</li>
        <li>Try a different brake cartridge.</li>
        <li>Press the thermal overload reset button on the contactor box.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Motor Starts Slowly / Fails to Reach Speed</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Check that correct voltage is being supplied.</li>
        <li>Adjust belt tension or replace worn belts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Motor Stopped Unexpectedly (Brake Did Not Fire)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Check if the Start/Stop paddle was bumped.</li>
        <li>Material may be overloading the detection system (wet/green wood) &mdash; use different wood or Bypass Mode.</li>
        <li>Consult System Status Codes.</li>
        <li>Check electrical power supply.</li>
        <li>Try a different brake cartridge.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Blade Slows During Cutting</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Check belt tension; replace worn belts.</li>
        <li>Ensure spreader/riving knife and fence are aligned with the blade.</li>
        <li>Verify blade is installed in the correct orientation.</li>
        <li>Verify motor is wired to match the power supply; check extension cord gauge.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Brake Activated Without Contact</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Check for conductive material touching the blade, arbor, or pulley &mdash; use Bypass Mode for conductive materials.</li>
        <li>Verify spreader/riving knife alignment (maintain 4&ndash;7 mm gap to blade).</li>
        <li>Check brake-to-blade spacing (1/16" to 1/8").</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Saw Vibrates Excessively</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Replace damaged or unbalanced blade.</li>
        <li>Move the saw to a level, even surface.</li>
        <li>Replace worn bearings or belts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cuts Not Clean or Even</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Replace or sharpen a dull blade.</li>
        <li>Clean blade of pitch, gum, or other buildup.</li>
        <li>Use the correct blade for the material and cut type.</li>
        <li>Align the rip fence with the blade.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Gears Sound/Feel Rough</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Clean and grease gears and elevation shafts.</li>
        <li>Release the elevation or tilt locking knob.</li>
      </ul>

